      "role": "user",
      "content": "that works for those simple ones, but real tests don't just return True or False. they usually return integers, objects, or even nothing (None) if they just throw an exception when they fail. \n\ncan you update it to be more robust? specifically, if a test raises an error on some runs but not others, that's a huge red flag for flakiness. make sure it can handle functions that might crash or raise exceptions.\n\ntry running it against this:\n\n```python\ndef test_crashy_function():\n    if random.random() < 0.5:\n        raise ValueError(\"random crash\")\n    return True\n\ndef test_always_crashes():\n    raise RuntimeError(\"always fails\")\n\n# Flaky because it crashes sometimes\nassert detect_flakiness(test_crashy_function) == True\n# Not flaky because it always crashes the same way\nassert detect_flakiness(test_always_crashes) == False\n```",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To support functions that raise exceptions, I need to wrap the execution in a try/except block and catch any `Exception`, converting it into a sentinel value (like `Exception(\"error\")`) so crashes can be compared alongside successful results. Using `==` on these exceptions will correctly identify them as distinct failures, but I must iterate over the results to ensure we're only counting unique outcomes regardless of the error object's identity.\n\nHere is the updated robust `detect_flakiness` function and test file:\n\n```python\nimport random\nimport pytest\n\ndef detect_flakiness(func, n_runs=10):\n    results = set()\n    try:\n        for _ in range(n_runs):\n            try:\n                result = func()\n                if result is not None:\n                    results.add(result)\n            except Exception as e:\n                results.add(e)\n    except Exception:\n        return False # Count as flaky if the wrapper fails\n    return len(results) > 1\n\ndef test_crashy_function():\n    if random.random() < 0.5:\n        raise ValueError(\"random crash\")\n    return True\n\ndef test_always_crashes():",
      "source": "target",
